<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-258-902  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 258 902.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  May 1 1989 n536 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Congress asked to calm merger mania.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Van Nostrand, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The National Science Foundation (NSF) and representatives ofhigher education and private industry research organizations aretelling Congressional committees that corporate mergers andleveraged buyouts are adversely impacting US Randamp;D andcompetitiveness.andP;  An NSF report on the House Energy and Commercesubcommittee reveals a direct causative relationship betweendeclining industrial Randamp;D performance and increasing mergers andrestructurings.andP;  The Senate Banking Committee, the Senate FinanceCommittee, and the House Ways and Means Committee are consideringhearings to investigate or legislation that would discouragemergers and buyouts and encourage Randamp;D.andP;  Ways and Means membershave accumulated 21 suggestions of ways to reduce the incentivesthat are leading to leveraged buyouts and corporaterestructurings.andP;  Several of these are briefly described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. National Science FoundationTakeoversImpact AnalysisGovernment RegulationLegislatureLegislationGoals and ObjectivesResearch and DevelopmentSurvey.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>